        <h2>                    1. Why I Made This Game                </h2>                <h3>                    I wanted to make this game because it was similar enough to League Invaders that I could use the things i'd learned working on League Invaders for my game, but it had enough unique elements that I could still learn new things. In addition, when the bare bones of my game were done, I could add on more elements, like a way to keep track of the high score, or refine things i'd worked on previously.                </h3>                <hr size='3'>                <h2>                    2. What I Learned                </h2>                <h3>                    I learned a lot from user testing. For one thing, the kids that played the game wanted it to be faster and have it be more difficult (with more projectiles and spikes to avoid). Because I had to play the game to see if certain bugs were fixed or if my changes were implemented, I was having enough trouble searching for bugs without the added difficulty of increased speed and difficulty. So, it was good to get perspective on the game from someone who wasn't worrying about the code. The kids also wanted extra challenges to make the game more interesting. Before that critique, I was focused on making the game actually work, but that helped me sit down and work on things I thought would be too difficult to add.                </h3>                <hr size='3'>                <h2>                    3. Architecture of My Game                </h2>                <h3>                    The main parts of my game are the GamePanel, GameObject and ObjectManagerK class. The GameObject class serves as a base for all the objects in my game, and adds variables to each one like a width, collision box and draw method. Some of the objects that extend or come from my GameObject class are the clouds, arrows, spikes and dragon. The ObjectManagerK takes these objects and helps them interact with each other. Some of the things ObjectManagerK does is creating and clearing ArrayLists of multiple objects like Arrows, checking collisions between projectiles and the Dragon object, and adding timers to objects so they don't appear on screen in the same location at the same time. My GamePanel class helps display everything from the ObjectManagerK class, as well as displaying the game panel and transitioning between different states.                </h3>                <hr size='3'>                <h2>                    4. Technical Implementation                </h2>                <h3>                    One aspect of the game i'm proud of is the Ground object. Since my first ideas for the game, I wanted to have a continuously moving Ground, but I didn't know how to go about that. I thought about making it one giant image that was constantly moving, but it would still have to end when players reached a certain point. So, I decided to make an ArrayList that would hold Ground objects and add them to the panel one after the other so that the Ground looked like it was constantly moving. This was tricky because it had to be very precise; if I put the Ground image a few pixels off there would either be a gap in the ground or it would not look seamless. In order to do this, I made a variable that tracked the top left corner of the Ground before the one I wanted to add, added the width of the previous ground to the variable and added a new Ground at this position.                </h3>                <hr size='3'>                <h2>                    5. Most Challenging Part                </h2>                <h3>                    The most challenging part of the project was starting it. I had an outline of what I wanted to include in the game, but making the large classes like the Main and GamePanel was confusing without a recipe to follow. Luckily, I knew roughly what to do from working on League Invaders, but it was still challenging to get a working game panel that switched between states. Once I had made a few classes, it was much easier to write the rest, since they all built off each other. The code for the Cloud objects was very similar to the Arrow objects, so a lot of the work was rewriting code and changing variables.                </h3>                <hr size='3'>                <h2>                    6. Future Fixes and Updates                </h2>                <h3>                    One fix I would like to make to the game is the fire breathing timer. In the game, your dragon character can breathe fire, but only after a certain time has passed and the timer is fully charged. When you shoot fire, the charge resets and it takes more time to get it fully charged again. I accidentally made it so that the timer that tracks how long it should be until you can breathe fire starts as soon as you open the menu, instead of when you press s to start the game. It's also hard to tell how long it takes to breathe fire. From play testing the game, I know that it's on average 20 seconds, but looking at the code it's hard to figure that out. There's a timer that increases the bar by five pixels every second until the bar is at 120 pixels, but that's unnecessarily complicated and should have been kept track of by a final integer.                </h3></body>                <hr size='3'>                <footer>                    We are a 501c(3) non-profit programming school.
